WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:00.600
Good afternoon.

2
00:00:02.240 --> 00:00:05.540
Vinod Balachandran from Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center in New York, and

3
00:00:05.580 --> 00:00:09.230
I'll be chairing this session on cancer vaccines, the next immunotherapy

4
00:00:09.300 --> 00:00:10.700
breakthrough.

5
00:00:13.260 --> 00:00:17.100
So cancer immunotherapy has come a long way since the first

6
00:00:17.110 --> 00:00:20.600
successful application of harnessing the immune system to fight cancer

7
00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:24.419
by surgeon William Coley at Sloan Kettering now over a century ago.

8
00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:29.620
And since then, many individuals, some highlighted here, have helped us discover

9
00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:31.740
the molecules and cells through which the immune system

10
00:00:32.619 --> 00:00:36.440
recognizes cancer, and in the modern era, develop

11
00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:40.420
strategies to harness this to treat cancer patients either directly or indirectly.

12
00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:45.420
But arguably, our last major discovery was now a decade ago,

13
00:00:46.020 --> 00:00:48.180
leaving us all wondering what's next.

14
00:00:49.540 --> 00:00:52.740
And a unifying theme that has really emerged from all of this work is that

15
00:00:53.620 --> 00:00:56.800
T cells recognize genetic byproducts of

16
00:00:56.840 --> 00:01:00.700
oncogenesis, neoantigens, to distinguish cancers as non-self.

17
00:01:01.570 --> 00:01:05.240
And T cell recognition of neoantigens is a major driver of the

18
00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:07.880
success of modern clinical immunotherapy, such as the checkpoints.

19
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.540
We know that tumors with more mutations respond

20
00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:15.060
and those with fewer mutations do not.

21
00:01:15.980 --> 00:01:19.540
So leading us to this question, if you can make T cells

22
00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:23.380
directly against neoantigens, either in tumors with

23
00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:27.360
few or many mutations, could you directly

24
00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:29.160
generate clinical impact?

25
00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:34.640
And in the past decade, we have seen significant progress towards this

26
00:01:35.420 --> 00:01:36.860
across the mutational space

27
00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:41.680
in cancers that are immunotherapy sensitive with many mutations, melanoma,

28
00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:46.290
work by Uğur Sahin and Cathy Wu demonstrating that RNA and peptide vaccines can

29
00:01:46.340 --> 00:01:47.840
make T cells against neoantigens.

30
00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:52.310
And at the polar opposite of the immunological and mutational

31
00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:56.280
spectrum in a cancer where immune therapy remains

32
00:01:56.320 --> 00:01:59.450
ineffective and with few mutations, pancreatic cancer, our work

33
00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:03.460
demonstrating that patients in fact make natural CD8 T cells against

34
00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:06.780
neoantigens that are long-lived and may impact clinical outcome.

35
00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:11.600
And since then, we now have multiple lines of evidence that there are many

36
00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:12.160
paths

37
00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:15.740
and platforms that can generate T cells against neoantigens.

38
00:02:16.180 --> 00:02:16.480
But

39
00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:19.960
does this lead to, in fact, clinical impact?

40
00:02:20.820 --> 00:02:24.720
And in the past few years, we have some early evidence that this might be

41
00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:25.360
the case.

42
00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:30.200
In 2023, our work in a very small Phase I

43
00:02:30.380 --> 00:02:34.260
non-randomized trial in pancreatic cancer, where we found adjuvant

44
00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:38.410
unmodified RNA neoantigen vaccine response was associated with

45
00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:41.680
delayed pancreatic cancer recurrence.

46
00:02:41.700 --> 00:02:45.660
And the following year, in 2024, work by the late Jeffrey

47
00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:49.440
Weber, stronger evidence in a Phase IIb randomized

48
00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:53.120
study in resected high-risk melanoma where adjuvant

49
00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:57.579
modified RNA neoantigen vaccines together with pembrolizumab

50
00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:01.340
improves recurrence-free survival compared to pembrolizumab alone.

51
00:03:02.560 --> 00:03:02.720
So

52
00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:04.220
with this

53
00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:08.570
early signs of clinical activity essentially spanning the mutational

54
00:03:08.680 --> 00:03:12.240
spectrum, it puts the field at a critical inflection point

55
00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:15.920
because what we really need now is broad-scale testing to close the gaps.

56
00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:20.500
And it is exciting now to see lots of clinical trials ongoing

57
00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:22.540
worldwide to test these concepts.

58
00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:25.600
It is also exciting to see

59
00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:29.020
we have the support of the federal government with the National Cancer Vaccine

60
00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:32.760
Initiative, launched earlier this year by the National Cancer Institute and the

61
00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:36.780
Foundation for National Institute of Health, to accelerate the development

62
00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:39.880
and access of therapeutic cancer vaccines nationwide.

63
00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:42.320
And this program is expected to launch in 2026.

64
00:03:43.940 --> 00:03:47.780
So as we embark on the horizon of

65
00:03:47.820 --> 00:03:51.260
cancer vaccines potentially being the next promising cancer

66
00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:55.200
immunotherapy, several fundamental challenges now continue to exist across

67
00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:58.900
all four pillars of cancer vaccinology as we head towards the next

68
00:03:58.940 --> 00:04:00.769
generation of more effective cancer vaccines.

69
00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:05.400
What is the optimal antigen? You heard a little bit about neoantigens today.

70
00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:09.060
You'll hear about, do you even need a tumor antigen in cancers that are checkpoint

71
00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:09.560
sensitive?

72
00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:14.240
What is the optimal platform that can generate immunity with clinical impact?

73
00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:18.101
Is it RNA? Is it peptide? Is it DNA? Perhaps all.

74
00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:21.579
What is the optimal host that can generate

75
00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:22.940
immunity?

76
00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:27.920
Is it cancers with few to many mutations, early disease, advanced disease?

77
00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:31.450
And finally, what are the optimal cells that you would need?

78
00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:35.940
CD8 cells, CD4 cells, both. How do they behave in

79
00:04:35.980 --> 00:04:36.330
tumors?

80
00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:40.280
So we have a full stack ahead of you for today's session,

81
00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:45.040
and each speaker will be followed by a short Q&amp;A, and then we'll have time

82
00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:48.160
for a short discussion at the end. And we'll begin with Cathy Wu.

83
00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:58.550
Thanks for that introduction. We've got a lot to cover, so I'll jump right in if

84
00:04:58.580 --> 00:05:02.560
the slides come up. And I want to thank Vinod and the organizers really

