CD4+ and CD8+ T

498
00:29:06.444 --> 00:29:10.164
cells in immunotherapy. Which would you

499
00:29:10.264 --> 00:29:14.224
say is the biggest priority in targeting, and what

500
00:29:14.244 --> 00:29:17.454
are the different ways that you address those separately?

501
00:29:17.584 --> 00:29:21.304
I also had another question regarding how would you address tumor

502
00:29:21.344 --> 00:29:23.714
heterogeneity in immunotherapies?

503
00:29:23.884 --> 00:29:26.304
Yeah. So I'll answer this second question first.

504
00:29:26.364 --> 00:29:29.964
So our personalized vaccines from the

505
00:29:30.004 --> 00:29:33.204
get-go, even back in 2017, were

506
00:29:33.264 --> 00:29:36.724
designed to specifically address tumor heterogeneity. Why?

507
00:29:37.164 --> 00:29:41.064
Because there's personalized. Second, because we're not going after one

508
00:29:41.144 --> 00:29:42.844
target, we're not going after two targets.

509
00:29:43.384 --> 00:29:46.964
At least in melanoma, we're typically targeting up to

510
00:29:47.184 --> 00:29:50.804
20 different targets. In GBM, it's harder, lower

511
00:29:50.844 --> 00:29:54.444
mutation burden, more typically 10, but a range of

512
00:29:54.804 --> 00:29:56.344
8 to 14, 15.

513
00:29:57.224 --> 00:30:01.204
If you look at the mRNA studies that are out there, they're targeting 34

514
00:30:01.224 --> 00:30:04.174
different epitopes, and many other studies out there are

515
00:30:05.004 --> 00:30:05.444
going with

516
00:30:06.284 --> 00:30:10.044
higher numbers. But I think the whole point of that is

517
00:30:10.104 --> 00:30:13.884
actually to head-on address the question of tumor

518
00:30:13.924 --> 00:30:17.684
heterogeneity. In terms of the targets, when we select our

519
00:30:17.724 --> 00:30:21.624
targets to include in the vaccine, it is driven a lot by

520
00:30:21.704 --> 00:30:25.344
the HLA binding score, based on our predictive

521
00:30:25.484 --> 00:30:29.144
algorithms. We also look at the expression of the

522
00:30:31.004 --> 00:30:33.454
mutated genes that we're targeting to ensure that those

523
00:30:34.784 --> 00:30:36.144
targets are expressed in the tumor.

524
00:30:37.724 --> 00:30:39.684
We can do one more short question.

525
00:30:40.704 --> 00:30:42.044
Great talk. So

526
00:30:43.104 --> 00:30:46.924
if you only look at shared antigens, so you did have some

527
00:30:46.984 --> 00:30:50.464
shared neoantigen in your pool of peptides.

528
00:30:50.524 --> 00:30:54.354
If you only look at those responses, do you see any correlation

529
00:30:54.724 --> 00:30:57.604
with survival, not as a pool response?

530
00:30:57.644 --> 00:31:00.704
So for clarification, these were all personal targets.

531
00:31:00.744 --> 00:31:02.874
We had zero shared amongst-

532
00:31:02.924 --> 00:31:04.724
I mean, sorry, driver mutation

533
00:31:05.556 --> 00:31:08.296
Even amongst the drivers, they were very individualized.

534
00:31:08.356 --> 00:31:11.796
So if the drivers were recurrent,

535
00:31:13.096 --> 00:31:16.616
I'm almost certain they're not the same mutation, same

536
00:31:16.626 --> 00:31:20.606
peptide sequence because of HLA restrictions from

537
00:31:20.676 --> 00:31:21.606
one patient to the other.

538
00:31:23.016 --> 00:31:24.476
So you do see the correlation?

539
00:31:24.836 --> 00:31:27.356
I'm happy to talk to you more about it later.

540
00:31:28.136 --> 00:31:28.496
Thank you.

541
00:31:29.076 --> 00:31:29.776
Thank you, Kathy.

542
00:31:33.336 --> 00:31:36.936
So for our next talk, we have our next generation star, Adam

543
00:31:37.016 --> 00:31:40.836
Griffin from MD Anderson, who will talk about mechanisms by

544
00:31:40.876 --> 00:31:44.206
which mRNA vaccines augment response to immune checkpoint blockade.

545
00:32:20.856 --> 00:32:23.596
Okay, excellent. Well, thank you so much for the opportunity to present this work

546
00:32:23.636 --> 00:32:24.806
on behalf of my colleagues.

547
00:32:25.716 --> 00:32:29.596
Today, I'm going to talk about mRNA vaccines and their ability to stimulate

548
00:32:29.616 --> 00:32:30.755
anti-tumor responses.

549
00:32:33.756 --> 00:32:34.576
Speak up.

550
00:32:34.616 --> 00:32:36.776
Okay. Can you all hear me okay? All right.

551
00:32:38.676 --> 00:32:39.616
Let's see. So,

552
00:32:40.536 --> 00:32:44.156
the setting that I want to focus on today is immune checkpoint blockade, which has

553
00:32:44.176 --> 00:32:48.096
really revolutionized the way we treat cancer, but remains ineffective in a

554
00:32:48.116 --> 00:32:52.096
subset of patients who lack preexisting anti-tumor immune responses.

555
00:32:52.756 --> 00:32:56.636
And one of the goals of personalized RNA nanoparticle vaccines is

556
00:32:56.676 --> 00:33:00.616
to provide this anti-tumor immunity in the patients who lack it at baseline.

557
00:33:00.956 --> 00:33:03.816
And there's been a lot of investigation in cancer vaccines in general, and

558
00:33:03.856 --> 00:33:07.356
particularly in the mRNA vaccine space over the last few years, with significant

559
00:33:07.396 --> 00:33:10.356
attention from both industry and the academic world.

560
00:33:10.736 --> 00:33:12.726
And a lot of this cancer vaccine work has

561
00:33:13.916 --> 00:33:15.856
been led by those on the panel with me.

562
00:33:15.936 --> 00:33:18.676
So I'm really honored to be here today to talk a little bit about what we're doing

563
00:33:18.736 --> 00:33:19.336
in this space.

564
00:33:20.316 --> 00:33:23.736
Overall, there's over 100 clinical trials now investigating these

565
00:33:23.776 --> 00:33:27.706
personalized RNA therapeutics, and that's not even to mention the DNA and

566
00:33:27.736 --> 00:33:30.316
peptide vaccines that are being evaluated.

567
00:33:30.996 --> 00:33:33.236
And this is how I got my start in cancer immunotherapy.

568
00:33:33.316 --> 00:33:36.756
We started working on a personalized RNA nanoparticle vaccine to treat patients

569
00:33:36.796 --> 00:33:37.556
with brain tumors.

570
00:33:38.656 --> 00:33:42.296
I'm showing data from a vaccine that we generated at the University of

571
00:33:42.336 --> 00:33:45.836
Florida. I was really fortunate to start working with this vaccine in mouse models.

572
00:33:45.896 --> 00:33:49.576
We ran a canine trial. I'm showing our first canine patient here, and

573
00:33:49.616 --> 00:33:52.796
these dogs did very well on vaccine.

574
00:33:52.816 --> 00:33:56.296
And now we've been able to launch a Phase 1 clinical study in patients with GBM

575
00:33:56.336 --> 00:33:59.736
that's currently ongoing, and we've treated about a half dozen patients, with the

576
00:33:59.756 --> 00:34:02.376
systemic RNA nanoparticle approach.

577
00:34:03.426 --> 00:34:07.016
But while developing these personalized vaccines, we realized a few of the

578
00:34:07.056 --> 00:34:10.256
complications of a personalized RNA nanoparticle vaccine approach.

579
00:34:10.756 --> 00:34:14.556
The first is the time that it takes to actually manufacture these vaccines.

580
00:34:14.616 --> 00:34:17.656
On the RNA side, we're talking about four to eight weeks for manufacturing.

581
00:34:17.716 --> 00:34:21.496
On the peptide side, it's a little longer, maybe 26 weeks, to actually

582
00:34:21.516 --> 00:34:25.216
produce these vaccines. And that really relegates these vaccines to the

583
00:34:25.296 --> 00:34:26.066
adjuvant setting,

584
00:34:27.076 --> 00:34:29.256
which is a delay from when the patients are diagnosed.

585
00:34:30.096 --> 00:34:33.656
The other major limitation is the cost of these personalized

586
00:34:33.696 --> 00:34:36.766
therapeutics. Obviously, if we're personalizing a vaccine for each individual

587
00:34:36.857 --> 00:34:40.226
patient, we're not able to manufacture these things in bulk, and so the cost of

588
00:34:40.276 --> 00:34:43.976
these therapeutics is significantly higher than if we could manufacture an

589
00:34:44.096 --> 00:34:47.986
off-the-shelf therapeutic. And then the final note about

590
00:34:48.076 --> 00:34:50.857
personalized vaccines, and really where I'm going to spend the bulk of my time

591
00:34:50.897 --> 00:34:53.647
today, is on the complexity of these vaccines.

592
00:34:54.156 --> 00:34:57.736
When we write grants and we write papers about these RNA vaccines, we like to

593
00:34:57.796 --> 00:35:01.436
propose this very linear story, where we are able to select

594
00:35:01.446 --> 00:35:05.236
targets from a tumor. We prescribe what the immune system should

595
00:35:05.296 --> 00:35:09.216
target, and we inject our RNA vaccine, and if we generate T cells

596
00:35:09.276 --> 00:35:13.236
reactive against those targets, we have this clear line to tumor regression.

597
00:35:13.636 --> 00:35:16.996
But in reality, I think that the reality here is a little more complex

598
00:35:17.356 --> 00:35:20.696
than what we like to portray. I'm going to show one experiment that kind of

599
00:35:20.756 --> 00:35:23.636
highlights this, and this is an experiment we ran in 2016.

600
00:35:24.176 --> 00:35:27.336
Again, at the time, we were developing a personalized vaccine, and our goal here

601
00:35:27.696 --> 00:35:30.736
was to show how important it was to personalize the vaccine.

602
00:35:31.156 --> 00:35:35.026
And so we used a metastatic model of osteosarcoma that

603
00:35:35.056 --> 00:35:38.446
was uniformly fatal in our mouse models, and we compared the

604
00:35:38.476 --> 00:35:41.916
personalized RNA vaccine here, labeled K7M2 in blue,

605
00:35:42.476 --> 00:35:46.176
to a GFP vaccine coding for green fluorescent protein, so

606
00:35:46.216 --> 00:35:50.026
nothing to do with the cancer. And what we initially wrote in the paper about

607
00:35:50.026 --> 00:35:53.496
this was that clearly personalization is important because the blue line is better

608
00:35:53.516 --> 00:35:57.276
than the gray line. But what I think is a much more interesting conclusion is

609
00:35:57.456 --> 00:35:58.956
what if we didn't have the blue line?

610
00:35:59.416 --> 00:36:02.926
Then our conclusion would have been that a GFP RNA nanoparticle

611
00:36:02.996 --> 00:36:06.856
vaccine doubles survival in an aggressive metastatic

612
00:36:06.896 --> 00:36:10.336
model of osteosarcoma. And I think that this is a much more interesting

613
00:36:10.396 --> 00:36:14.136
conclusion because this raises the possibility that we could generate a

614
00:36:14.196 --> 00:36:18.076
universal RNA therapeutic that we could use to prime the immune response in a

615
00:36:18.116 --> 00:36:21.936
large number of patients without knowing anything about the antigens that are

616
00:36:21.976 --> 00:36:24.236
specifically present in their tumor.

617
00:36:24.246 --> 00:36:27.116
And so we've been tracking this story down, and we published it last year in

618
00:36:27.256 --> 00:36:30.576
"Nature Biomedical Engineering" with the idea that we could use a systemic RNA

619
00:36:30.656 --> 00:36:34.646
nanoparticle vaccine to really prime immune responses without

620
00:36:34.656 --> 00:36:36.236
knowing anything about the tumor antigens.

621
00:36:36.926 --> 00:36:37.816
Along the way, though,

622
00:36:38.996 --> 00:36:42.336
the world changed, and we were presented with a really unique

623
00:36:42.436 --> 00:36:46.356
opportunity, because 3.4 billion doses of an mRNA

624
00:36:46.476 --> 00:36:49.776
vaccine were administered to target a non-tumor antigen.

625
00:36:49.816 --> 00:36:53.256
I'm talking about the COVID vaccine, which is targeting the spike protein

626
00:36:53.276 --> 00:36:55.316
in the COVID virus.

627
00:36:56.216 --> 00:36:59.936
And so what we wanted to test was whether the COVID mRNA

628
00:36:59.976 --> 00:37:03.936
vaccine could also be used to prime anti-tumor immune responses, and

629
00:37:03.976 --> 00:37:07.912
maybe sensitize tumors to immune therapy.So to answer this question,

630
00:37:07.972 --> 00:37:11.552
we looked back at patients treated with immune therapy at MD Anderson.

631
00:37:11.872 --> 00:37:15.572
I'm showing first data with patients with lung cancer who happened to receive a

632
00:37:15.632 --> 00:37:18.382
COVID vaccine around the time they initiated immune therapy.

633
00:37:18.892 --> 00:37:22.552
Here we're looking at a 100-day window before or after they initiated ICI,

634
00:37:23.132 --> 00:37:25.792
and we found this really striking result, which was that those patients who

635
00:37:25.812 --> 00:37:29.632
happened to receive the vaccine had significantly improved overall survival

636
00:37:29.692 --> 00:37:33.452
relative to patients who didn't receive a COVID mRNA vaccine.

637
00:37:33.492 --> 00:37:37.092
This was true for patients with stage III and IV non-small cell lung cancer, and it

638
00:37:37.132 --> 00:37:41.032
was really specific to this one context of an mRNA vaccine

639
00:37:41.072 --> 00:37:44.412
plus ICI. This didn't work in patients who received chemotherapy.

640
00:37:44.472 --> 00:37:47.801
They didn't seem to benefit from the vaccine, and it also didn't work for other

641
00:37:47.812 --> 00:37:51.692
vaccines like influenza or pneumonia vaccines, where we saw no benefit

642
00:37:51.772 --> 00:37:54.092
of vaccination in timing with ICI.

643
00:37:55.092 --> 00:37:58.412
We also replicated this finding in patients with stage IV melanoma.

644
00:37:58.492 --> 00:38:01.852
Here I'm showing a propensity-matched cohort of patients with stage IV melanoma

645
00:38:01.892 --> 00:38:05.392
with overall survival on the left and progression-free survival on the right, which

646
00:38:05.432 --> 00:38:09.232
really showed the strong signal of a relationship between the timing of

647
00:38:09.272 --> 00:38:10.232
these two therapeutics.

648
00:38:11.072 --> 00:38:14.492
Now, I want to acknowledge, though, this data was published in October, but it was

649
00:38:14.532 --> 00:38:17.742
really designed as a signal-finding analysis, and there were some limitations to

650
00:38:17.772 --> 00:38:21.552
our initial study. One is this allowed for a healthy vaccinee

651
00:38:21.572 --> 00:38:24.992
bias because we were comparing vaccinated patients against unvaccinated

652
00:38:25.012 --> 00:38:28.212
patients. There were also relatively small cohorts here.

653
00:38:28.242 --> 00:38:32.052
And we also had a problem with immortal time bias because we allowed vaccination

654
00:38:32.172 --> 00:38:35.642
after receipt of ICI. And although we tried to control for this statistically, it's

655
00:38:35.672 --> 00:38:39.152
a very difficult thing to really tease out what the effect of that immortal time

656
00:38:39.212 --> 00:38:43.012
bias is. And finally, there were also some error effects in here that the patients

657
00:38:43.052 --> 00:38:46.962
who got vaccine in 2021 were being compared against patients who

658
00:38:46.962 --> 00:38:50.882
didn't have the opportunity to get vaccine in 2020, or may be less likely to get

659
00:38:50.892 --> 00:38:54.422
the vaccine in 2022 or 2023. And so to address some of

660
00:38:54.492 --> 00:38:58.332
these problems, we went to our biostatisticians and we said, "How can we design

661
00:38:58.652 --> 00:39:02.152
the most robust possible analysis to really

662
00:39:02.192 --> 00:39:05.612
determine whether there's a signal here to follow?" And so what they came up with

663
00:39:05.672 --> 00:39:09.592
was a target trial emulation, where we essentially pre-specify if we were going to

664
00:39:09.632 --> 00:39:12.952
have run a clinical trial, what that trial would look like, and then we apply that

665
00:39:12.992 --> 00:39:16.732
to our historical cohort. In this setting, we did a pan-tumor

666
00:39:16.772 --> 00:39:20.342
analysis, so we enrolled all patients at MD Anderson who had

667
00:39:20.352 --> 00:39:23.632
received immune checkpoint blockade in a two-year

668
00:39:23.672 --> 00:39:27.392
period. And then we only looked at those patients in our group of

669
00:39:27.412 --> 00:39:30.972
interest, only patients who received the vaccine before they got ICI.

670
00:39:31.072 --> 00:39:33.932
So we eliminated the immortal time bias problem with this analysis.

671
00:39:34.472 --> 00:39:37.532
And then we used statistical techniques, including inverse probability weighting,

672
00:39:37.872 --> 00:39:40.992
to really adjust for the other variables between the groups.

673
00:39:41.261 --> 00:39:44.472
And what we found was that after we really carefully controlled for as many

674
00:39:44.532 --> 00:39:48.472
variables as possible, this relationship stood very strong, and those patients who

675
00:39:48.552 --> 00:39:51.332
happened to receive the vaccine within 30 days prior to

676
00:39:52.152 --> 00:39:55.452
receiving immune therapy lived significantly longer than those who didn't across

677
00:39:55.472 --> 00:39:59.112
this pan-tumor cohort. We also found that this relationship persisted

678
00:39:59.232 --> 00:40:03.152
in different eras. So in 2021, when the vaccine use was very prevalent,

679
00:40:03.212 --> 00:40:07.112
we saw a strong relationship. And also in 2022, when the vaccines

680
00:40:07.392 --> 00:40:07.852
were less

681
00:40:08.872 --> 00:40:12.352
widely utilized, we still saw a strong relationship with

682
00:40:12.412 --> 00:40:12.892
survival.

683
00:40:14.012 --> 00:40:17.792
We also, to cover our bases, wanted to make sure that this wasn't an MD Anderson

684
00:40:17.872 --> 00:40:21.732
specific effect, and so we've now replicated this analysis with our colleague

685
00:40:21.792 --> 00:40:23.612
Jake New, who's at Scripps Health.

686
00:40:24.212 --> 00:40:28.012
And he was able to find the same effects with the COVID mRNA vaccine, boosting

687
00:40:28.032 --> 00:40:30.632
responses to immune checkpoint blockade in our retrospective studies.

688
00:40:30.992 --> 00:40:34.842
And similar to our cohorts, he didn't see effects for other

689
00:40:34.872 --> 00:40:38.712
vaccines like influenza. But all this retrospective data we really have to

690
00:40:38.752 --> 00:40:41.992
take with a grain of salt. And so we took these findings to the lab to see if we

691
00:40:42.012 --> 00:40:45.492
could replicate them. We essentially made a version of the BioNTech

692
00:40:45.812 --> 00:40:49.032
COVID mRNA vaccine that's available at CVS following their published

693
00:40:49.072 --> 00:40:52.792
specifications, and we used it as a therapeutic in our mouse models.

694
00:40:52.832 --> 00:40:56.052
And here I'm showing data from two established tumor models, melanoma

695
00:40:56.072 --> 00:40:59.752
B16-F0 on the left and then a Lewis lung carcinoma model of

696
00:40:59.812 --> 00:41:01.292
non-small cell lung cancer on the right.

697
00:41:01.732 --> 00:41:04.832
In both settings, we waited until the tumors were large, at least 100 millimeters

698
00:41:04.912 --> 00:41:08.732
cubed, and then we had started administering ICI with or without a COVID

699
00:41:08.812 --> 00:41:12.742
vaccine intramuscularly. And really strikingly, we found that this

700
00:41:12.792 --> 00:41:16.541
intramuscular COVID vaccine was able to sensitize these tumors to immune checkpoint

701
00:41:16.592 --> 00:41:17.072
blockade.

702
00:41:18.752 --> 00:41:21.792
So in thinking about how this was happening, we thought back to the way that we had

703
00:41:21.812 --> 00:41:23.332
designed our personalized vaccine.

704
00:41:23.852 --> 00:41:27.592
And with our personalized RNA vaccine, we found that it was a potent

705
00:41:27.671 --> 00:41:29.252
activator of the innate immune response.

706
00:41:29.592 --> 00:41:33.452
After we gave this vaccine, 24 hours later, we activated essentially every myeloid

707
00:41:33.492 --> 00:41:37.352
cell in the body. We were looking in the liver, the spleen, the lung,

708
00:41:37.412 --> 00:41:41.292
the tumor, the lymph nodes. Everywhere we looked, we would see dendritic cells and

709
00:41:41.352 --> 00:41:44.292
macrophages that were strongly activated after receipt of this vaccine.

710
00:41:45.072 --> 00:41:48.192
Now, we didn't know if we would see the same thing with the COVID vaccine, and the

711
00:41:48.232 --> 00:41:52.152
reason is the COVID vaccine was specifically designed not to produce

712
00:41:52.162 --> 00:41:55.822
a strong interferon alpha burst. So if you'll recall, in

713
00:41:55.932 --> 00:41:59.812
2023, the Nobel Prize was awarded for the discovery that we could

714
00:41:59.872 --> 00:42:03.432
use N1-methylpseudouridine to silence toll-like receptor 7 activation and

715
00:42:03.492 --> 00:42:05.892
allow mRNA to be safer to use in humans.

716
00:42:06.252 --> 00:42:10.012
It also increases the translation efficiency of that messenger RNA, and that

717
00:42:10.052 --> 00:42:12.272
technology is incorporated into the COVID vaccine.

718
00:42:12.592 --> 00:42:15.572
So we weren't sure if we'd be able to see the same increase in interferon alpha and

719
00:42:15.612 --> 00:42:19.192
myeloid activation with the COVID mRNA vaccine that was available.

720
00:42:20.352 --> 00:42:24.092
So we first started with a panel of cytokines to see what was happening in our

721
00:42:24.132 --> 00:42:27.672
mouse models. But in the mice, the number one most

722
00:42:27.732 --> 00:42:31.572
upregulated cytokine after receipt of this vaccine was actually interferon alpha.

723
00:42:32.492 --> 00:42:36.012
And so what we think is happening here is that although the N1-methylpseudouridine

724
00:42:36.052 --> 00:42:39.992
modification is very effective at minimizing TLR7 activation,

725
00:42:40.332 --> 00:42:42.112
there's a backdoor activation pathway,

726
00:42:42.932 --> 00:42:46.492
where mRNA, when it's combined with a lipid nanoparticle, actually triggers a

727
00:42:46.552 --> 00:42:50.512
second intracellular receptor called MDA5, and that receptor is

728
00:42:50.532 --> 00:42:53.392
responsible for the surge in interferon alpha that we're seeing in our mouse

729
00:42:53.472 --> 00:42:57.052
models. We think the reason this happens is that when you combine the

730
00:42:57.152 --> 00:43:00.422
RNA with a lipid nanoparticle, you actually form higher molecular weight

731
00:43:00.992 --> 00:43:03.112
structures that we think are activating MDA5.

732
00:43:03.132 --> 00:43:06.412
We have a little more work to do there to really tease that story out, but that's

733
00:43:06.452 --> 00:43:09.242
where our current thoughts are and how we're getting this

