1196
01:10:25.260 --> 01:10:28.720
get data that's really very similar to what's seen from

1197
01:10:28.760 --> 01:10:31.560
transcriptional analysis of responsive tumors.

1198
01:10:33.560 --> 01:10:34.560
Okay. So

1199
01:10:35.420 --> 01:10:39.160
I think just to summarize, I gave you an optimized approach for adoptive

1200
01:10:39.220 --> 01:10:42.760
cell therapy. So in vitro, there might be ways

1201
01:10:43.140 --> 01:10:46.920
to improve over the culture using a PI3 kinase

1202
01:10:46.980 --> 01:10:50.380
inhibitor. We have brand-new data on combining different

1203
01:10:50.420 --> 01:10:54.240
inhibitors, and we have data in both mouse and human TILs to

1204
01:10:54.300 --> 01:10:58.060
suggest that we can also sustain some level of

1205
01:10:58.180 --> 01:11:00.700
stemness in those cell populations.

1206
01:11:01.340 --> 01:11:04.840
Then in vivo, I think vaccination works quite well to boost

1207
01:11:05.220 --> 01:11:07.860
the CD8 response and remodel the tumor environment.

1208
01:11:08.310 --> 01:11:11.240
And then the spatial transcriptomic analysis says that the

1209
01:11:11.300 --> 01:11:15.260
vaccine enhances the immune cell infiltrate, which

1210
01:11:15.300 --> 01:11:18.520
is critical. And then I think it's interesting

1211
01:11:19.040 --> 01:11:22.680
that the vaccine and the stem-like cells alter the tumors

1212
01:11:22.700 --> 01:11:26.500
themselves and make them more responsive through a variety of pathways

1213
01:11:26.860 --> 01:11:30.780
for killing. And then the other thing, I think, this is probably motherhood

1214
01:11:30.800 --> 01:11:34.500
and apple pie, is that the transcriptional analysis of TME

1215
01:11:34.540 --> 01:11:38.480
is really critical, and it might be critical prognostically, and it might

1216
01:11:38.520 --> 01:11:42.260
be critical to guide therapeutic interventions because T

1217
01:11:42.380 --> 01:11:45.850
cells may or may not work depending on the tumor

1218
01:11:46.240 --> 01:11:50.040
microenvironment. So I'll close and say all this

1219
01:11:50.060 --> 01:11:50.800
work was done

1220
01:11:51.860 --> 01:11:55.320
originally by Andrew Shizuka and Jeffrey Lin, and then Faizah

1221
01:11:55.360 --> 01:11:59.260
Baharom. That was the first part of the talk, but this was all really led

1222
01:11:59.300 --> 01:12:03.160
by Dalton Hermans, who was a phenomenal graduate student who finished

1223
01:12:03.220 --> 01:12:06.820
with help from Sloan and Ben. And I'll stop, take

1224
01:12:06.840 --> 01:12:07.380
questions.

1225
01:12:17.400 --> 01:12:18.780
I think we can do one question

1226
01:12:19.580 --> 01:12:22.280
and then move the other questions to the discussion session. Yep.

1227
01:12:23.300 --> 01:12:27.280
Hey, Bob. So that was really nice. I'm curious about the PI3 kinase

1228
01:12:27.340 --> 01:12:31.180
inhibitor studies. So clearly the cells work better, and

1229
01:12:31.280 --> 01:12:32.940
you cure more of the tumors early.

1230
01:12:33.740 --> 01:12:37.660
But if you don't, if they're subject to chronic stimulation, are they

1231
01:12:37.760 --> 01:12:41.570
more durable, or do they get exhausted and burn out the same as

1232
01:12:41.600 --> 01:12:43.800
normal cells? Is there a permanent change in those cells?

1233
01:12:44.360 --> 01:12:46.420
Yeah. So that's a good question, John.

1234
01:12:46.480 --> 01:12:49.880
And so we don't have data on the durability yet.

1235
01:12:49.920 --> 01:12:53.880
And so we're doing that now, but that's a really good question of how

1236
01:12:53.940 --> 01:12:57.460
long, how durable they are and how long that will persist.

1237
01:12:57.520 --> 01:13:01.460
As you can imagine, the protection starts to wane after

1238
01:13:01.480 --> 01:13:03.580
about 30 days. And so,

1239
01:13:05.240 --> 01:13:09.100
it's interesting. In the tumor itself, when you look at the transcriptomes of

1240
01:13:09.140 --> 01:13:12.860
each of the cells three days later, there's not that much of a

1241
01:13:12.900 --> 01:13:13.430
difference,

1242
01:13:14.620 --> 01:13:17.300
because they've probably been activated.

1243
01:13:17.380 --> 01:13:21.080
And so the stem-like cells, and you might have better insight into this,

1244
01:13:21.120 --> 01:13:22.600
really convert quickly.

1245
01:13:22.840 --> 01:13:23.540
Yeah.

1246
01:13:23.940 --> 01:13:27.860
So I agree with you that the key question would be durability, and

1247
01:13:27.900 --> 01:13:29.780
we should do that.

1248
01:13:29.840 --> 01:13:30.060
Thanks.

1249
01:13:30.400 --> 01:13:34.100
If you could maybe approach Bob afterwards, since we're running behind. Thank you.

1250
01:13:49.788 --> 01:13:52.208
Thank you to the organizers and my co-chairs.

1251
01:13:57.188 --> 01:14:00.908
So pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma, PDAC, considered

1252
01:14:00.928 --> 01:14:04.448
the immunologically invisible tumor because it

1253
01:14:04.528 --> 01:14:08.208
has few neoantigens, few T cells, is

1254
01:14:08.408 --> 01:14:11.848
insensitive to checkpoint inhibitors, and typifies the nearly

1255
01:14:11.968 --> 01:14:15.938
80% of cancers that similarly have few mutations and

1256
01:14:16.068 --> 01:14:19.838
insensitive to checkpoints. PDACs also have very high unmet medical

1257
01:14:19.928 --> 01:14:23.848
need. Second deadliest cancer in the United States, 90% of

1258
01:14:23.928 --> 01:14:26.308
PDAC patients die with current treatments.

1259
01:14:26.768 --> 01:14:30.308
But fascinatingly, 10% in fact survive long-term.

1260
01:14:30.708 --> 01:14:34.428
Why? Unknown. So for the past decade, we've been studying these patients with

1261
01:14:34.468 --> 01:14:38.408
really two questions in mind: How do they do this, and how could we replicate this?

1262
01:14:38.868 --> 01:14:42.708
And what we have learned is that these patients mount natural T cell immunity

1263
01:14:42.718 --> 01:14:46.398
to PDAC, characterized by many CD8 T cells in their

1264
01:14:46.428 --> 01:14:50.228
primary tumors, that although PDACs have few mutations, in fact

1265
01:14:50.268 --> 01:14:53.918
recognize somatic passenger mutated neoantigens that you can

1266
01:14:53.968 --> 01:14:57.508
identify a priori based upon their unique immunogenic properties.

1267
01:14:58.008 --> 01:15:01.628
Immunity is amplified by innate lymphocytes in the microenvironment

1268
01:15:02.088 --> 01:15:04.098
through the formation of tertiary lymphoid structures.

1269
01:15:04.648 --> 01:15:08.628
You can also deliver these neoantigens to other PDAC patients with RNA to make

1270
01:15:08.688 --> 01:15:12.448
lots of CD8 cells, and these CD8 cells, in fact, have quite exceptional

1271
01:15:12.468 --> 01:15:16.348
longevity and function. So over the past decade, we have gone from discovery

1272
01:15:16.388 --> 01:15:20.148
to clinical development of two promising new immunotherapies for PDAC, and

1273
01:15:20.248 --> 01:15:23.828
today I'm excited to tell you about our work on the first PDAC RNA vaccine.

1274
01:15:24.508 --> 01:15:28.468
Now, this story really starts now 10 years ago, when we became interested in, is

1275
01:15:28.488 --> 01:15:32.268
there natural immunity in PDAC? And to answer this, we identified

1276
01:15:32.288 --> 01:15:35.908
cohorts of short and long-term PDAC survivors and found that

1277
01:15:35.948 --> 01:15:39.918
these long-term survivors had primary tumors enriched in many CD8

1278
01:15:39.968 --> 01:15:43.908
T cells, leading us to the question, what are the antigens and could they

1279
01:15:43.968 --> 01:15:47.808
be neoantigens? Now, the conventional thinking at the time was

1280
01:15:47.848 --> 01:15:51.428
cancers with a few mutations would generate a fewer

1281
01:15:51.528 --> 01:15:55.248
neoantigens, and this was really an extrapolation from studies in

1282
01:15:55.268 --> 01:15:59.088
checkpoint inhibition, where we knew that tumors with more mutations

1283
01:15:59.168 --> 01:16:01.968
respond and fewer mutations do not.

1284
01:16:02.368 --> 01:16:06.288
So leading to the assumption that neoantigen generation in human cancer was

1285
01:16:06.348 --> 01:16:10.098
purely linear. So if you have more mutations,

1286
01:16:10.668 --> 01:16:12.038
suited for neoantigen therapy,

1287
01:16:12.948 --> 01:16:16.228
fewer mutations, unsuited for neoantigen therapy.

1288
01:16:16.288 --> 01:16:19.908
So really to probe this, and as we already had proof of

1289
01:16:19.948 --> 01:16:23.868
concept of immunotherapy success in lots of tumors with more

1290
01:16:23.888 --> 01:16:27.188
mutations, melanoma, lung cancer, others, we wanted to

1291
01:16:27.228 --> 01:16:30.448
understand, could immunotherapy really be possible in cancers with few

1292
01:16:30.488 --> 01:16:34.428
mutations? And if we could unlock neoantigen vaccination for pancreatic

1293
01:16:34.448 --> 01:16:37.668
cancer, perhaps this could unlock vaccines for many more cancers.

1294
01:16:38.408 --> 01:16:42.268
So we developed a new antigen quality model to identify the immunogenic

1295
01:16:42.428 --> 01:16:46.348
properties of neoantigens based upon their biophysical characteristics

1296
01:16:46.428 --> 01:16:50.048
of non-selfness and selfness. And what we found was tumors

1297
01:16:50.168 --> 01:16:53.788
enriched in high quality, but not quantity neoantigens

1298
01:16:53.908 --> 01:16:57.788
identified patients with longer survival, introducing

1299
01:16:57.868 --> 01:17:01.848
that tumors with very few mutations could harbor neoantigens that are both

1300
01:17:01.888 --> 01:17:04.228
clinically relevant and targetable.

1301
01:17:04.238 --> 01:17:07.828
And this was supported by the observation that we could find a CD8 T

1302
01:17:07.928 --> 01:17:11.858
cells recognizing these high-quality neoantigens in primary tumors

1303
01:17:11.908 --> 01:17:15.788
of rare survivors with identical clones persisting in the circulation

1304
01:17:15.828 --> 01:17:19.488
for a decade later. So suggesting that these neoantigens could stimulate

1305
01:17:19.568 --> 01:17:22.688
long-term immunological memory CD8 T cells

1306
01:17:22.968 --> 01:17:26.148
specifically, even if it had very few neoantigens.

1307
01:17:26.808 --> 01:17:30.628
And furthermore, when we examined how these primary tumors enriched in

1308
01:17:30.648 --> 01:17:34.188
neoantigens evolved out to recurrent tumors, what we found is

1309
01:17:34.348 --> 01:17:38.257
selective editing of cancer clones harboring these high quality,

1310
01:17:38.468 --> 01:17:42.078
but not other neoantigens. So in sum, more evidence of

1311
01:17:42.268 --> 01:17:44.408
natural neoantigen immunity in PDAC.

1312
01:17:45.008 --> 01:17:48.928
So what we were finding was natural neoantigen immunity in PDAC

1313
01:17:48.968 --> 01:17:52.428
may impact PDAC survival. But as most PDACs in fact

1314
01:17:52.588 --> 01:17:56.358
harbored neoantigens, it raised a question, could inducible neoantigen immunity

1315
01:17:56.528 --> 01:18:00.308
also impact PDAC survival? And as these neoantigens derive

1316
01:18:00.368 --> 01:18:04.188
from patient-specific passenger mutations, we felt the best technology

1317
01:18:04.268 --> 01:18:07.648
for rapid custom cancer vaccination really was to use RNA.

1318
01:18:08.368 --> 01:18:12.348
So we proposed and convinced colleagues at GenTech and BioNtech that although

1319
01:18:12.368 --> 01:18:15.928
they may think PDAC might be the least likely cancer suited for a neoantigen

1320
01:18:15.968 --> 01:18:19.688
vaccination or perhaps for any immunotherapy, perhaps it is the

1321
01:18:19.828 --> 01:18:23.768
most suited cancer. And this led to this investigator-initiated trial

1322
01:18:23.778 --> 01:18:27.628
where we resected primary PDACs in New York, and we shipped the tumors to

1323
01:18:27.728 --> 01:18:31.488
colleagues in Germany, who then custom manufacture individualized vaccines for each

1324
01:18:31.508 --> 01:18:33.488
patient called autogenous vimeral.

1325
01:18:33.828 --> 01:18:37.608
So after surgery, we treat patients with a PL1 blocking antibody,

1326
01:18:38.008 --> 01:18:41.388
custom vaccination, chemotherapy, and a vaccine booster.

1327
01:18:41.888 --> 01:18:45.488
Now, key question in this trial was, can vaccines generate

1328
01:18:45.908 --> 01:18:49.678
neoantigen-specific T cells in a cancer with very few mutations?

1329
01:18:50.548 --> 01:18:54.088
Which we realized early required sensitive methods for

1330
01:18:54.108 --> 01:18:58.038
detection, because for a single neoantigen administered

1331
01:18:58.088 --> 01:19:01.958
as a mutation spanning 27-mer, there is in fact a very

1332
01:19:02.068 --> 01:19:05.848
large combinatorial neoepitope HLA space, only a

1333
01:19:06.088 --> 01:19:09.848
fraction of which is recognized by an individual TCR leading to clonal

1334
01:19:09.888 --> 01:19:13.768
expansion. So trying to monitor the entirety of the immune response from

1335
01:19:13.808 --> 01:19:17.548
the epitope HLA side using tetramers is really impractical and

1336
01:19:17.628 --> 01:19:21.528
leads to an incomplete answer. So we wanted to understand this from the TCR

1337
01:19:21.648 --> 01:19:23.698
side using longitudinal TCR sequencing.

1338
01:19:24.248 --> 01:19:28.088
Now, if you just do longitudinal TCR sequencing in the peripheral blood, as

1339
01:19:28.148 --> 01:19:31.848
shown here, this is over 20 time points in five years in a

1340
01:19:31.888 --> 01:19:35.528
single patient, you can see you get lots of clones in the peripheral blood.

1341
01:19:35.968 --> 01:19:39.548
So we developed a new technology called CloneTract to specifically

1342
01:19:39.688 --> 01:19:43.228
identify vaccine-induced T cells, as you can see in this

1343
01:19:43.268 --> 01:19:46.668
particular green line, an individual T cell clone expanding after

1344
01:19:46.808 --> 01:19:50.728
prime and boost. And you can now identify all clones, and

1345
01:19:50.988 --> 01:19:54.348
later what we showed was this population contains vaccine

1346
01:19:54.508 --> 01:19:56.168
neoantigen-specific T cell clones.

1347
01:19:56.388 --> 01:20:00.308
So from a large population of clones, identifying really a

1348
01:20:00.388 --> 01:20:02.908
very small fraction that is induced by the vaccine.

1349
01:20:03.458 --> 01:20:07.028
So now that you've found these clones, essentially you can track their persistence

1350
01:20:07.128 --> 01:20:10.768
over time. And what we find here is that after prime and boost,

1351
01:20:11.048 --> 01:20:13.648
these clones have a median estimated lifespan of

1352
01:20:14.168 --> 01:20:17.988
7.7 years. So the vaccine-induced CD8 T

1353
01:20:18.048 --> 01:20:21.708
cells, in fact, have exceptional longevity despite

1354
01:20:21.748 --> 01:20:24.476
post-vaccination chemotherapy.Okay.

1355
01:20:24.516 --> 01:20:28.196
So in this trial, what we found was that these vaccines can induce

1356
01:20:28.236 --> 01:20:31.616
neoantigen-specific T cells in 50% of unselected

1357
01:20:31.796 --> 01:20:35.676
PDAC patients, and these CD8 T cell clones are in fact

1358
01:20:35.686 --> 01:20:39.196
substantial in magnitude, recognizing single and multiple

1359
01:20:39.236 --> 01:20:43.076
neoantigens. And looking at a follow-up time of 36

1360
01:20:43.136 --> 01:20:47.096
months, we found vaccine responders had a median recurrence-free survival

1361
01:20:47.136 --> 01:20:51.116
that was not reached compared to non-responders, and this correlation was not

1362
01:20:51.196 --> 01:20:55.056
confounded by other factors, neither from host immunologic fitness

1363
01:20:55.116 --> 01:20:59.056
differences, because both of these populations generate similar immune

1364
01:20:59.136 --> 01:21:02.196
responses to a control RNA vaccination, which is SARS-CoV-2.

1365
01:21:03.136 --> 01:21:06.556
Okay. So, so far what we know is that in pancreatic

1366
01:21:06.576 --> 01:21:10.176
cancer, these vaccines induce CD8 T cells of high

1367
01:21:10.216 --> 01:21:11.926
magnitude, longevity, and function.

1368
01:21:12.676 --> 01:21:15.156
And these CD8 T cells are in fact de novo.

1369
01:21:16.036 --> 01:21:19.846
This includes a polyclonal, polyfunctional, high avidity population that

1370
01:21:19.936 --> 01:21:23.436
over time transitions into memory-like T cells with a

1371
01:21:23.476 --> 01:21:25.556
tissue-resident memory-like phenotype.

1372
01:21:26.206 --> 01:21:29.496
And immunity correlates with delayed recurrence at three-year follow-up.

1373
01:21:29.836 --> 01:21:31.736
Correlation does not imply causation.

1374
01:21:31.816 --> 01:21:34.236
We are testing causation in a randomized trial currently.

1375
01:21:34.776 --> 01:21:38.756
And finally, resistance appears to occur due to outgrowth of non-vaccine targeted

1376
01:21:38.796 --> 01:21:42.616
cancer clones. Okay. So, so far this, but what is in

1377
01:21:42.656 --> 01:21:46.056
fact happening right now? So if you look at five years now

1378
01:21:46.096 --> 01:21:49.716
post-treatment, you can see that these vaccine-induced T cell clones in fact

1379
01:21:49.756 --> 01:21:53.236
continue to persist in the peripheral blood at very high

1380
01:21:53.276 --> 01:21:57.076
magnitudes, including up to 1% of all T cells in the

1381
01:21:57.116 --> 01:22:00.976
blood. And this, you can see, encompasses several individual T

1382
01:22:01.056 --> 01:22:04.986
cell clones, some which persist and others do not, seemingly in

1383
01:22:04.996 --> 01:22:08.806
the absence of antigen. So raising the question, could this

1384
01:22:08.836 --> 01:22:12.296
perhaps be related to specific features of vaccine neoantigens?

1385
01:22:12.896 --> 01:22:16.506
So to answer this, we go back to our neoantigen quality model,

1386
01:22:16.896 --> 01:22:20.876
where we estimate immunogenic features of an antigen based upon a similarity

1387
01:22:20.936 --> 01:22:24.856
to known antigens and selfness we determine based

1388
01:22:24.896 --> 01:22:28.096
upon how the mutated epitope differentially binds either the

1389
01:22:28.156 --> 01:22:31.686
MHC or the TCR with respect to the wild type allele.

1390
01:22:32.166 --> 01:22:35.716
And of course, for antigen selection for vaccination, we determine or

1391
01:22:35.836 --> 01:22:39.636
estimate these parameters a priori, but now we can in

1392
01:22:39.716 --> 01:22:43.596
fact directly measure this and ask whether any features correlate with T

1393
01:22:43.676 --> 01:22:47.496
cell longevity. So to do this, we turn to an assay that we

1394
01:22:47.516 --> 01:22:51.476
developed in vitro to specifically identify neoantigen-specific T

1395
01:22:51.556 --> 01:22:55.276
cell clones we call CloneMap. And using this assay, we

1396
01:22:55.376 --> 01:22:59.156
identify neoantigen-specific T cell clones in vitro, and

1397
01:22:59.236 --> 01:23:02.056
using cloning and epitope mapping, we confirm specificity.

1398
01:23:02.136 --> 01:23:05.596
So you can see here for these individual six clones here, they

1399
01:23:05.636 --> 01:23:09.136
selectively recognize this 14-mer epitope, but not

1400
01:23:09.236 --> 01:23:13.176
epitopes of smaller length. And then for each of these individual T cell

1401
01:23:13.256 --> 01:23:16.476
clones, we specifically analyze how these clones

1402
01:23:16.656 --> 01:23:20.336
cross-react against a mutated compared to the wild type epitope,

1403
01:23:20.756 --> 01:23:24.396
mutated indicated in red, wild type epitope indicated in

1404
01:23:24.496 --> 01:23:28.196
blue. And you can see here that some clones cross-react, whereas

1405
01:23:28.476 --> 01:23:32.016
other clones do not, demonstrating really a range of a

1406
01:23:32.096 --> 01:23:35.536
self-reactivity that extends beyond a different

1407
01:23:35.596 --> 01:23:39.586
individual patient to different patients, different HLAs,

1408
01:23:39.956 --> 01:23:42.816
as well as to different epitope lengths as well.

1409
01:23:43.696 --> 01:23:46.836
So overall, what we find is that these

1410
01:23:46.896 --> 01:23:50.856
vaccine-induced T cells in fact bind the mutated epitope

1411
01:23:51.216 --> 01:23:54.256
more strongly compared to the wild type epitope.

1412
01:23:54.636 --> 01:23:58.536
But interestingly, cross-reactivity of the clone to

1413
01:23:58.576 --> 01:24:02.416
the wild type epitope correlates with enhanced longevity in vivo,

1414
01:24:02.756 --> 01:24:06.736
suggesting that signaling through the wild type epitope perhaps may

1415
01:24:06.756 --> 01:24:10.456
be a factor that allows these T cells to persist in vivo.

1416
01:24:10.496 --> 01:24:14.426
Okay, so when we vaccinate, we think we want these vaccines to be able to

1417
01:24:14.456 --> 01:24:18.216
make new T cells. Why? Well, if your cancers have very

1418
01:24:18.316 --> 01:24:22.136
few mutations to begin with, there's few

1419
01:24:22.216 --> 01:24:24.256
T cells there, so you have to make them.

1420
01:24:24.276 --> 01:24:28.146
In cancers with more mutations where there are more endogenous T cells,

1421
01:24:28.636 --> 01:24:32.566
we believe some fraction of these T cells are likely to be amplified by

1422
01:24:32.596 --> 01:24:36.465
checkpoint inhibitors. And as we are co-administering these drugs together in

1423
01:24:36.496 --> 01:24:40.296
the clinic, ideally, you may want to have new T cells to avoid

1424
01:24:40.375 --> 01:24:44.296
overlap with checkpoint inhibitors and theoretically to broaden

1425
01:24:44.375 --> 01:24:48.066
your therapeutic index. Now, how do you know you're making new T cells?

1426
01:24:48.476 --> 01:24:52.406
